The paper proposes a framework for utilizing structured linguistic information such as constituency trees and dependency trees to improve the performance of machine comprehension algorithms. This falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP) and specifically, the subfield of syntactic parsing. Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. Additionally, the proposed algorithm framework involves deep neural networks, which suggests that it could also fall under cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). The evaluation of the approach is done on the SQuAD dataset, which is a popular benchmark for question answering systems, indicating that it could also belong to cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Finally, the paper mentions the use of attention models, which are commonly used in computer vision tasks, suggesting that it could also fall under cs.CV (Computer Vision).
